\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b a}) Subsp. {\b sylvestris}: Variable; stems usually branched, but in alpine plants often simple and c. 10 cm high. Epicalyx-scales usually 4. Calyx (12-)15-22 × 4-5 mm; teeth ovate-lanceolate, obtuse. Petal-limb 8-12 mm, usually contiguous.{\i  Throughout the range of the species except parts of the W. Mediterranean region}.
\par 

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b b}) Subsp. {\b siculus} (C. Presl) Tutin,{\i  Feddes Repert.}{\b  68}: 190 (1963) ({\i D. siculus} C. Presl,{\i  D. longicaulis} Ten.,{\i  D. gasparrinii} Guss.): Robust, usually branched. Epicalyx-scales 4-8. Calyx 24-30 × 5-7 mm; teeth lanceolate, acuminate. Petal-limb 10-15 mm, usually contiguous, dentate or denticulate.{\i  Sardegna and Sicilia}.
\par 

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b c}) Subsp. {\b longicaulis} (Ten.) Greuter & Burdet,{\i  Willdenowia}{\b  12}: 187 (1982) ({\i D. contractus} Jan ex Nyman,{\i  D. godronianus} Jordan, {\i D. sylvestris} subsp. {\i garganicus} (Grande) Pignatti): Like subsp. ({\b b}) but often glaucous; calyx 18-28 mm, the teeth long, triangular, subacute or obtuse; petal-limb 7-9 mm. 2n = 30.{\i  Mediterranean region, from S. Spain to W. Jugoslavia}.
\par 

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b d}) Subsp. {\b nodosus} (Tausch) Hayek, {\i Prodr. Fl. Penins. Balcan.}{\b  1}: (1924) ({\i D. nodosus }Tausch): Stems usually puberulent below. Epicalyx-scales (2-)4-6(-8). Calyx 15-20 × c. 4 mm. Petal-limb 8-10 mm, usually contiguous, dentate or denticulate. •{\i  W. part of Balkan peninsula}.
\par 

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b e}) Subsp. {\b bertisceus} Rech. fil.,{\i  Feddes Repert.}{\b  38}: 150 (1935). Stems usually simple. Epicalyx-scales (2-)4-6(-8). Calyx (10-)12-16(-20) × 5 mm. Petal-limb 5-6 mm, dentate or denticulate. •{\i  W. & S. Jugoslavia, Albania}.
\par 

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b f}) Subsp. {\b tergestinus} (Reichenb.) Hayek,{\i  loc. cit.} (1924) ({\i D. tergestinus} (Reichenb.) A. Kerner): Plant somewhat glaucous. Epicalyx-scales 2(-4). Calyx 15-20 × 4-5 mm. Petal-limb c. 6 mm, usually not contiguous, entire. 2n = 30. •{\i  W. Jugoslavia, Albania; E. Italy} ({\i Gargano}).
\par 

