\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 65. D. caryophyllus }L., {\i Sp. Pl. }410 (1753). Laxly caespitose, usually glaucous perennial up to 80 cm; woody basal part of stem rather long and not very thick. Leaves 2-4 mm wide, linear, nearly flat. Flowers strongly fragrant. Epicalyx-scales 4, c. ¼ as long as calyx, broadly obovate, cuspidate. Calyx usually 25-30 × 5-7 mm, nearly cylindrical; teeth c. 5 mm, acuminate to subobtuse. Petal-limb 10-15 mm, usually contiguous, glabrous, purple, rarely pink or white, dentate. 2n = 30.{\i  Widely cultivated for ornament and occasionally naturalized, but apparently not known wild, except perhaps in some Mediterranean countries}. *Gr *It *Sa *Si [Ga Hs].
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28 {\b D. arrostii} C. Presl in J. & C. Presl,{\i  Del. Prag.}{\b  1}: 60 (1822), from Sardegna and Sicilia, appears to differ only in the patent epicalyx-scales, somewhat shorter calyx, and uniformly pale pink petals.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28 {\b D. multinervis} Vis.,{\i  Fl. Dalm. }{\b 3}: 164 (1852), described from the Adriatic island of Pomo, but now extinct, appears to have been close to, or possibly an abnormal variant of{\b  65}, characterized by the 5- to 9-veined leaves which are described as broadly lanceolate, and by the shorter calyx.
